In [ ]:
for i, row in narrowed_prices.groupby('symbol'):
    plt.figure()
    x = row['date']
    y = row['close']
    plt.title('{} - {}'.format(i, row['name'].any()))
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('Share Price')
    plt.plot(x, y)
In [ ]:
for i, sector in narrowed_prices.groupby('sector'):
    mean = []
    for j, date in sector.groupby('date'):
        mean.append((j, date['close'].mean()))
    plt.plot(*zip(*mean))
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Share Price')
    plt.title(i)
    plt.show()

Share prices should be normalized, Large plunge in IT because Google dropped hard in 2015, while all other companies in IT increased, but had lower share prices.

np_scaled = narrowed_prices.copy()
for column in ['open', 'close', 'low', 'high','volume']:
    np_scaled[column] = (np_scaled[column] - np_scaled[column].mean())/np_scaled[column].std()

Some markets have consistently underpreformed compared to others. Meaning, if a shareholder held stock in both a Consumer Discretionary company and an Industrials company in 2010, both shares would increase in value on average by 2017, but the Consumer Discretionary company would increase at a much greater rate.
